<b><font size=+1>
List:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2">namedroppers</a>
Subject:    <a href="?t=95837888300007&r=1&w=2">Relative naming</a>
From:       <a href="?a=95837693600009&r=1&w=2">Joe Weening &lt;JJW () SU-AI ! ARPA&gt;</a>
Date:       <a href="?l=namedroppers&r=1&w=2&b=198604">1986-04-24 23:41:00</a></font>
[Download RAW <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026688&q=mbox">message</a> or <a href="?l=namedroppers&m=95837759026688&q=raw">body</a>]</b>

There seems to be agreement that a sequence of possible completions for a
partially specified domain name should be tried.  If one of these is to
treat the name as fully specified, however, then it will cause a request
to go to a root server, to ask for a top-level domain that probably does
not exist.

Too many of these might cause a significant load on the root servers.  Has
any of this been noticed yet?  (Perhaps resulting from implementations
that don't yet complete partial specificatiions.)  It suggests that the
completions further down in the tree should be tried first, which
fortunately is also the most reasonable assumption about what the user
intended.  However, a single character mistyped could still result in a
request to go all the way to the root.  This somehow seems wrong.

						Joe

